Understanding the General Ledger and the COA
11/26/2018 • 2 minutes to read
The general ledger stores your financial data, and the chart of accounts shows the accounts that all general
ledger entries are posted to. Business Central includes a standard chart of accounts that is ready to support
your business.
General Ledger Setup and General Posting Setup
The setup of the general ledger is at the core of financial processes because it defines how you post data.
On the General Ledger Setup page, y

ou specify how to handle certain accounting issues in your company,
such as:
Invoice rounding details
Address formats
Financial reporting
Similarly, on the General Posting Setup page, you specify how you want to set up combinations of general
business and general product posting groups. Posting groups map entities like customers, vendors, items,
resources, and sales and purchase documents to general ledger accounts. You fill in a line for each combination
of business posting group and product po

sting group. For more information, see Posting Group Setups
The Chart of Accounts
The chart of accounts shows all general ledger accounts. From the chart of accounts, you can do things like:
View reports that show general ledger entries and balances.
Close your income statement.
Open the G/L account card to add or change settings.
See a list of posting groups that post to that account.
View separate debit and credit balances for a single account
You can add, change, or delete general ledger acco

unts. However, to prevent discrepancies, you can't delete a
general ledger account if it's data is used in the chart of accounts.
Account Categories
You can personalize the structure of your financial statements by mapping general ledger accounts to account
categories.
The G/L Account Categories page shows your categories and subcategories, and the G/L accounts that are
assigned to them. You can create new subcategories and assign those categories to existing accounts.
You create a category grou

p by indenting other subcategories under a line on the G/L Account Categories
page. This makes it easy for you to get an overview, because each grouping shows a total balance. For example,
you can create subcategories for different types of assets, and then create category groups for fixed assets
versus current assets.
You can specify whether the accounts in each subcategory must be included in specific types of reports. The
account categories help define the layout of your financial statements.

For example, the default balance statement has a subcategory for Cash under Current Assets. If you want the
balance statement consider petty cash and checking, you can:
1. Add two new subcategories. One for petty cash, and one for your checking account.
2. Specify the additional report definition Cash Accounts for these subcategories.
3. Indent them under the Cash subcategory.
The next time you generate account schedules your balance statement will show a total balance for cash and
two lines w

ith balances for petty cash and the checking account.

Working with Accounting Periods and Fiscal Years
11/26/2018 • 3 minutes to read
Accounting periods, which are also known as reporting periods, are periods of time for which a company or
organization reports financial performance, for example, by generating their income statement or balance sheet.
Typically, accounting periods refer to the company's fiscal yea

r, which can contain several accounting periods, such
as months or quarters.
For many companies the fiscal year does not align with the calendar year. For example, the fiscal year might end on
June 30th rather than December 31st. For newly created companies, the fiscal might actually be longer than 12
months.
Business Central only requires accounting periods only if you want to close an income statement, or run data
compression tasks.
You can use accounting periods in reporting. For example, whe

n you are reviewing posted entries on the
Balance/Budget page where the reporting interval can be specified. One of the options you may specify to report
by accounting period. You can also build an account schedule that compares results for different accounting
periods.
Creating a new fiscal year
You can create accounting periods in bulk, by using eh Create Fiscal Year batch job, or manually.

If the accounting periods in your fiscal year have different durations, like the 4 4 5 calendar used in retail, you can
manually set it up.
1. Choose the  icon, enter Accounting Periods, and then choose the related link.
2. In the Starting Date field, enter the date on which the fiscal year starts. The Name field will show the name of
the month.
3. Ch

oose the New Fiscal Year check box to indicate that this is the first period in the year. Business Central will

use this period to determine which periods to close at year end.
4. Repeat steps 2 and 3 for each remaining period.
Closing a Fiscal Year
Closing the fiscal year is one of the tasks for closing the books. After you close a fiscal year, the Closed and Date
Locked check boxes are selected for all periods in the year. You cannot reopen a year or clear the check boxes.
NNOOTTEE
You must

always have at least one open fiscal year. When closing a year, ensure that a new year has been created. Also, note
that after you close one year, you cannot change the starting date of the following year.
1. Choose the  icon, enter Accounting Periods, and then choose the related link.
2. Choose the Close Year action.
Posting Entries to a Closed Fiscal Year
Although a fiscal year is closed, you can still post general ledger entries to it. When you do, the entries are marked
as posted to a close

d fiscal year and the Prior Year Entry check box is selected. By default, the check box is not
displayed on the page, but you can add it. The next steps are to close the income statement accounts and transfer
the year's results to an account in the balance sheet. Repeat these steps each time you post entries to a closed fiscal
year.

The Heart: The Marvel of Life Sciences 
The heart, often revered as the seat of emotions, is fundamental to life itself. As a 
muscular organ, it serves as the engine of the cardiovascular system, ensuring that blood 
circulates throughout the body. In this exploration of the heart through the lens of life 
sciences, we will delve into its anatomy, physiology, and significance, while also 
considering some intriguing facts and recent advances in cardiac research. 
 
Anatomy of the Heart 
The hum

an heart is a remarkable structure, roughly the size of a fist, and is located 
slightly left of the center of the chest. It consists of four chambers: two upper 
chambers known as the atria and two lower chambers called the ventricles. The right side 
of the heart receives deoxygenated blood from the body and pumps it to the lungs for 
oxygenation, while the left side circulates oxygen-rich blood to the entire body. 
 
The heart is encased in a protective layer of tissue called the pericardium.

Each chamber 
has its own valves—namely, the tricuspid, pulmonary, mitral, and aortic valves—that 
ensure the unidirectional flow of blood. These valves open and close in response to 
pressure changes, allowing for efficient circulation. 
 
Physiology of the Heart 
Understanding the physiology of the heart involves appreciating how it operates in 
harmony with other body systems. The heart's pumping action is regulated by electrical 
impulses that initiate each heartbeat. These impulses origina

te in a specialized cluster 
of cells called the sinoatrial (SA) node, often referred to as the heart's natural 
pacemaker. 
 
The heart pumps an astonishing amount of blood throughout our lives. On average, it beats 
around 100,000 times a day, circulating approximately 5 liters of blood per minute. This 
constant flow of blood is crucial for transporting oxygen and nutrients to tissues and 
organs, while simultaneously removing carbon dioxide and metabolic waste. 
 
In addition to its mechanic

al function, the heart also plays a vital role in hormone 
regulation. For instance, it releases atrial natriuretic peptide (ANP), which helps 
regulate blood pressure and fluid balance. The intricate relationship between the heart 
and these physiological processes underscores its importance in maintaining overall 
health. 
 
The Heart in Health and Disease 
While the heart is remarkably resilient, it is also vulnerable to various diseases and 
conditions. Cardiovascular diseases (CVD) remain o

ne of the leading causes of morbidity 
and mortality worldwide. Risk factors such as high blood pressure, high cholesterol, 
diabetes, obesity, and a sedentary lifestyle can significantly increase the likelihood of 
developing heart disease. 
 
Common heart conditions include coronary artery disease, heart failure, arrhythmias, and 
valvular heart disease. Each of these conditions can arise from a myriad of factors, 
encompassing genetic predisposition, lifestyle choices, and environmental influ

ences. 
 
Recent advances in life sciences have paved the way for improved diagnostic techniques 
and treatment options. For instance, the advent of non-invasive imaging techniques, such 
as echocardiography and cardiac MRI, has revolutionized how we diagnose and monitor heart 
conditions. Furthermore, the development of minimally invasive surgical procedures and 
breakthroughs in medication—such as statins for cholesterol management—has significantly 
enhanced patient outcomes. 
 
The Heart-Bra

in Connection 
Intriguingly, recent studies have highlighted the intricate connection between the heart 
and the brain, often referred to as the heart-brain axis. Emotions such as stress, 
anxiety, and depression can significantly impact heart health. Conversely, poor heart 
health can also affect cognitive function, leading to an increased risk of conditions 
such as dementia. 
 
Incorporating heart-heathy practices, such as regular physical activity, a balanced diet, 
and mindfulness technique

s, can contribute to overall well-being and mitigate the risk of 
both cardiovascular and mental health issues. 
 
The Future of Heart Research 
The field of cardiac research continues to flourish, with scientists exploring innovative 
treatments and therapies. Stem cell therapy, for example, holds promise for regenerating 
damaged heart tissues, while gene therapy is being investigated for its potential to 
correct genetic defects leading to heart disease. 
 
Additionally, wearable technology

and mobile health applications are playing an 
increasingly pivotal role in heart health management. These advancements allow for 
continuous monitoring of heart rate and rhythm, providing valuable data for both patients 
and healthcare providers. This real-time feedback empowers individuals to take proactive 
steps in managing their heart health. 
 
Conclusion 
The heart is not merely a pump; it is a complex organ integral to our understanding of 
life sciences. From its anatomy and physiology

to its pivotal role in health and disease, 
the heart encapsulates the intricate connections within our bodies and the broader 
implications for health. As we continue to explore and innovate in cardiac science, we 
move closer to unlocking new possibilities for preventing, diagnosing, and treating heart 
conditions, ultimately promoting a healthier future for all.

In a small village nestled between rolling hills and calm waters, the community gathered 
each summer for the Festival of the Fading Sun, a celebration of renewal and healing. 
Amongst laughter and music, an elderly woman named Elara became the keeper of stories, a 
role she cherished dearly. This year, she decided to share a tale that wove the past of 
humanity’s struggle with cancer into the fabric of their lives today. 
 
She began with a whisper of history, “Long ago, in the land of ancient

Egypt, the first 
civilizational whispers of a disease began to surface. The Egyptians were masters of 
papyrus and ink, and they documented their findings on the fragile leaves. Ancient 
medical papyri described maladies that resembled what we know today as cancer. A tumor 
was named 'khet,' and though they lacked our scientific language, they understood the 
pain it brought.” 
 
The villagers leaned in, their faces illuminated by flickering lanterns. 
 
“In the centuries that followed, the Gre

eks and Romans delved deeper. Hippocrates, the 
father of medicine, spoke of ‘karkinos’—the crab—making a comparison between the shape of 
the tumor and the sea creature’s claws. ‘Humors’ were blamed, and in the grand 
amphitheaters, fierce discussions ignited among philosophers and healers on how to combat 
this malady.” 
 
Elara paused, her gaze drifting to the starry sky. “The path to understanding was a long 
one. Through the Middle Ages, cancer fell into darkness, attributed to divine punis

hment 
or sin. Many suffered in silence, wrapped in stigma and fear, while the seeds of 
knowledge lay dormant.” 
 
As the fire crackled, a child named Amir raised his hand. “Did anyone ever find a way to 
help them?” 
 
“Ah, little one,” Elara replied with a warm smile. “That leads us to a turning point. In 
the 18th and 19th centuries, the world began to awaken. Doctors like Edwin Smith 
uncovered more than ancient wisdom; they sought methods to understand and treat cancer. 
An unexpected ally

emerged as well—charitable organizations and foundations.’” 
 
Elara recalled the rise of institutions filled with hopeful minds seeking answers. “In 
1937, the American Cancer Society was founded, igniting awareness and advocacy, which 
became paramount in our battle. Communities banded together, hoping for brighter 
tomorrows.” 
 
The villagers exchanged knowing glances, feeling the power of solidarity in the air. 
 
“But the story does not end there,” Elara continued, her voice growing stron

ger. “The 
20th century unveiled a revolution in medicine—a surge of research, the discovery of 
chemotherapy, radiation, and immunotherapy. Here, hope intertwined with science. Patients 
became warriors, battling not just for survival but for life itself.” 
 
Elara shared stories of brave souls who faced the daunting journey through cancer 
treatments—of friends sitting by hospital bedsides, of families banding together to 
support one another. She spoke of the first successful attempts at risk

y surgeries that 
removed tumors, a delicate dance between precision and faith, where every heartbeat 
mattered. 
 
“Your ancestors discovered remarkable resilience, but the fight was not solely technical. 
The histories of cancer told tales of human spirit. In every corner of the world, patient 
advocates spoke up, raising their voices for better care and research funding. 
Organizations were formed, and awareness campaigns blossomed. These collective efforts 
led to remarkable advancements, bu

t also a deeper understanding: that it was not just 
about the disease—it was about the people who endured it.” 
 
The night grew deeper, and the villagers were absorbed in the narrative, feeling as if 
they were part of a larger tapestry woven with both sorrow and triumph. 
 
Elara concluded, “Today, we stand on the shoulders of giants. Though the fight against 
cancer is ongoing, we must remember that with every challenge, hope finds a way. We are 
the bearers of this legacy, and through compa

ssion and knowledge, we can change the 
future. Each one of you is part of this story—of healing, remembrance, and of power.” 
 
As the festival reached its zenith, the villagers lit lanterns to symbolize hope and 
healing, sending them into the night sky. They honored their history, not only 
celebrating the strides made against cancer but also cherishing the human connections 
that blossomed from this enduring struggle. 
 
In that moment, under the stars, they understood that history did not

merely belong to 
the past; it echoed loudly in their hearts, a testament to the enduring spirit of 
humanity and the promise of tomorrow.
